1. Introduction¶

Artificial Neural Networks have proved themselves to be very powerful tools in performing tasks (namely classification) on raw data. As an example on the ImageNet dataset, modern neural network models have reached 91% Top-1 accuracy for classification (https://paperswithcode.com/sota/image-classification-on-imagenet). However, what these models learn that is enabling them to perform so well is mostly still a mystery.

It's clear that for us human beings, even though we have unique concepts for each type of entity, we still group entities together not only based on obvious taxonomic similarities (for example lions and tigers are both "cats") but also based on entity attributes (dogs and cats both have fur). For example, dogs and cats are more similar than dogs and birds not just because the first pair are taxonomically similar (both mammals), but they are more similar because they share many attributes (and arguably this is the source of the taxonomic distinction). Dogs and Cats both: have 4 legs, have fur, have tails, etc. Though it may seem obvious that these are true of most mammals, when first seeing these animals it's already clear that they are more similar than the pair "dog and bird" despite not knowing what "mammal" means. So although our semantic knowledge may be organized in a symbolic taxonomy as we mature, initially that cannot be the case since we learn from the raw data presented by the world and not through symbolic manipulation representing entities in the world.

Following this line of reasoning, two reasonable question arise.

  1. How do neural networks organize semantic information about concrete nouns?
  2. Can utilizing attributes lead to higher classification performance?

This is what this project aims to explore. The organization of concrete nouns in a neural network has been investigated before, however that was in a a symbolic setting (see Motivation section). This project extends that work by looking at semantic organization based on raw images as opposed to symbolic one-hot encoded vectors.

Motivation¶

To get an idea of what has just tbeen described above, let's look at an example.

In this example, we're going to be exploring the semantic organization of a very simple neual network. We will look at a few natural language sentences of entities and their atrtibutes (with respect to some relation) and see how the networks entity representations differ among entites by the end of training. Entities are mapped to attributes/properties via predicates relations.

This is a reimplementation of the paper linked here: https://www.nature.com/articles/nrn1076. Note: The idea for the example was reimplemented from the paper, but the code was written by me.

In [3]:
def make_vectors(list_of_xs):
    x_to_vectors = {}
    
    # Create identity matrix size of input
    vectors = np.eye(len(list_of_xs)).astype(np.float32)
    
    # Map each item in input to unique row from identity matrix
    for index, x in enumerate(list_of_xs):
        x_to_vectors[x] = vectors[index]
        
    return x_to_vectors

We then use the function above to create the one-hot encoded vectors for the entities, relations, and attributes.

In [4]:
items_to_vectors = make_vectors(items)
relations_to_vectors = make_vectors(relations)
attributes_to_vectors = make_vectors(attributes)

In order to learn mappings, we have to create propositions that involve the appropriate entity-relation-attribute connections. So to do that I create a list of propositions in natural language which will serve as the training exmaples for the neural network. These propositions are what I gather were used from the taxonomic organization in the paper above.

This function takes a list of natural language propositions and returns a list of tuples of the one-hot encoded version of the proposition. Here, we want the output to be of the form ((entity, relation), attribute), so that for the neural network the input is the entity and relation and the output is the attribute. More explicitly, we are leanring a {(entity, relation) -> attribute} mapping. Since this function uses a look up, it does not work with words not already in the lists created above.

In [6]:
def parse_propositions(propositions):
    parsed_propositions = []
    
    for proposition in propositions:
        # Splits the proposition based on spaces
        proposition_parts = proposition.split()
        
        # Full attribute vector to be used for each proposition
        targets = np.zeros(len(attributes))
        
        # Sum the one-hot encoded vectors for the attributes for this proposition
        for part in proposition_parts[2:]:
            targets += attributes_to_vectors[part.replace(',', '')]
            
        # Get one-hot encoded vector for entity and relation
        item = items_to_vectors[proposition_parts[0]]
        relation = relations_to_vectors[proposition_parts[1]]
        
        # Package the entity-relation-attribute combo
        parsed_propositions.append(((item, relation), targets))
        
    return parsed_propositions

Now we use the function defined above to actually parse the natural language propositions that we defined earlier.

In [7]:
learning_data = parse_propositions(propositions)

Now we begin to actually create the network so that we can analyze how it organizes semantic information.

Here we create the simple artificial neural network that will use the training examples (vector propositions) above to learn representations of the entities based on the relations and constrained by the attributes. The layer design (2 hidden, 1 output) follows the design in the paper above. We keep the architectre simple so as to minimize the number of other influencing factors on the networks organization.

In [8]:
class semantic_network(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_items, num_relations, num_attributes):
        super(semantic_network, self).__init__()
        
        # Layer representing the entity to internal representation of the network
        self.item_to_rep = nn.Linear(num_items, num_items)
        
        # Layer used to combine the representation from above with the predicate relation
        self.combine = nn.Linear(num_items + num_relations, num_items + num_relations)
        
        # Layer used to predict the attributes based on the information above
        self.complete_query = nn.Linear(num_items + num_relations, num_attributes)
        
    def forward(self, x):
        # Extract the entity and the relation
        item = x[0]
        relation = x[1]
        
        # Generate the representation
        representation = self.item_to_rep(item)
        
        # Combine representation and relation
        hidden = self.combine(torch.cat((representation, relation), 0))
        
        # Predict attributes
        out = self.complete_query(hidden)

        return out, representation

We now instatiate the model using information about the number of entities, the number of relations, and the number of attributes. We then set a high number for the number of epochs to ensure that the representations for the entities have a chance to settle into a stable position and are not still changing. We set the learning rate to a standard value that will allow the network to learn fast. We use a Binary Cross Entropy with Logits since we are essentially doing multiclass and multilabel classification. We use Stochastic Gradient Descent so that training proceeds quickly.

In [9]:
model = semantic_network(8, 4, len(attributes))

epochs = 2000
learning_rate = 0.01

lossfunction = nn.BCEWithLogitsLoss()
optimizer = optim.SGD(model.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)
In [10]:
for epoch in range (epochs):
    total_loss = 0
    #train loop
    for (item, relation), attribute in learning_data:
        # Get example for training data list and convert vectors into torch tensors
        (item, relation), attribute = (torch.from_numpy(item), torch.from_numpy(relation)), torch.from_numpy(attribute)
        
        #forward
        logits, representation = model((item, relation))
        
        #loss
        loss = lossfunction(logits, attribute)
        total_loss += loss.item()
        
        #backward
        loss.backward()
        
        #update
        optimizer.step()
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        
    # Print the training progress to ensure learning is stable
    if epoch % 200 == 0:
        print(f"Loss: {total_loss/len(learning_data)}")
        print()

Now that training is complete, we look at the intermediate representations of the different entities to determine how the representations differ among the different entities. We first use linkage dendrogram to determine the similarties of the representations based on euclidean distance, then we look at the raw representation to get a qualitative feel on how they differ. The linkage dendrogram will give is a sense of how the representations cluster taxononically, and the raw representations will may give us insight into what the different dimensions of the representation mean.

As you can see it is very clear that the representations of things that we would as humans would count as similar are actually similar. After a single transformation from the one-hot encoded vector, the entities representations look similar to other entities like it. For example salmon has a very similar representation to sunfish, and the euclidean distance of pine and oak are very close as compared to pine (or oak) and any other category.


So it seems like taxonomic organizationn can be learned in a distributed way. Unfortunately, it does not seem like the raw representations give us any information as to what the different dimension of the vector representation could actually mean.























However, as mentioned above we as humans clearly do not learn based on purely symbolic inputs as done above. So, moving forward we will be looking at the use of raw images as input.























Questions¶






















To reiterate I will be augmenting an image dataset, so that I can create a network that learns based on attributes of the image as opposed to simply the using the single classification label. In doing this we will be able to get a sense of whether augmenting a dataset with handcrafted intermediate features will boost the learning signal in classification tasks. This also may allow for the creation of algorithms that perform in more human like ways since we are restricting the ways that the classification algorithms can learn by introducing inductive biases.

Data Curation/Augmentation/Exploration¶






















In this analysis we will be using the CIFAR10 dataset. The CIFAR-10 dataset is a dataset consisting of 60000 32x32 images distributed over 10 classes with 6000 images per class. I am using this dataset because it has a small number of classes making it reasonable to create natural language propositions for each class, and it will be reasonable to visualize and statiscally test the differences between the different classes. This dataset also has an even distribution of classes among the images meaning no particular class will be biased over others. CIFAR-10: https://www.cs.toronto.edu/~kriz/cifar.html


To access the dataset, I will be using the torchvision.datasets library. I then transform the images into normalized tensors with range [-1, 1] so that it is easier for the network to learn (by stabilizing the gradient, preventing it from growing it too large).

As you can see using an image distance metric it's clear that, numerical similarity between images is not enough to learn the kinds of taxonomic similarities that were discussed above. Based on euclidean distance the airplane and horse images were closest, then the bird and horse images, and lastly the horse and horse images. What we  would have wanted was (1) horse-horse (2) horse-bird (3) horse-airplane, since based on properties that ranking reflects the pairs of entities that are most similar.























Set up the Artificial Neural Network and Train it¶






















Next, we get right to creating the network that will learn based on attributes as opposed to learning based on the class category. To do this we will use pytorch like above. Here we use a convolutional neural network as opposed to simple network, so that we can take advantage of the local properties present in the images. Simple networks destroy information about that locality of features since they flatten everything. By using a convolutional network, we may be able to map feature patterns in the images to the attributes.


In terms of architecture, We use a simple architecture (Conv-relu-maxpool-conv-relu-maxpool-conv-fully_connected network), this is so we can take advantage of the power of the convolutional layers while keeping the amount of extra influences that could cause the network to perform well (that are not strictly due to attributes) to a minimum.



















In [37]:



     


class image_network(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_relations, num_attributes):
        super(image_network, self).__init__()
        
        # Sequence of transformations to create image representation
        self.image_to_rep = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Conv2d(3, 8, 3),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.MaxPool2d(2, 2),
            nn.Conv2d(8, 16, 3),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.MaxPool2d(2, 2),
            nn.Conv2d(16, 32, 3),
            nn.Flatten(),
            nn.Linear(512, 64)
        )
        
        # Layer to ombine the image representation with the relation
        self.combine = nn.Linear(64 + num_relations, 64 + num_relations)
        
        # Predict the attributes based on the image+relation combo
        self.complete_query = nn.Linear(64 + num_relations, num_attributes)
        
    def forward(self, img, relation):
        # Create the image representation
        representation = self.image_to_rep(img)
        
        # Combine the image and relation
        hidden = self.combine(torch.cat((representation, torch.unsqueeze(relation, 0)), 1))
        
        # Make attributes prediction
        out = self.complete_query(hidden)

        return out, representation

Here we instantiate the model, set the learning parameters, loss function, and the optimizer. We use a low number of epochs because based on earlier testing it seems that the representations settle after just one 1 epoch. The loss function is Binary Cross Entropy with Logits Loss since we are doing a mix of multiclass and multilabel classification.


We train the network by getting the (image, label) example from the data loader, and then training on the four propositions that are relevant to the entity in the image. By doing this we ensure the network is able to train on all of the proositions that are relevant to each entity. This will allow the network weights to adjust such that similar entities will get similar representations based on attribute similarity.


We also log the differentiation dynamics. Now we are not only going to look at the final cluster of representations, but we are going to look at all the intermediate clsutering of representations while the training is going on. This will give us a sense of how the network chooses to group/differtiate between different entities a it learns from the attributes.



















In [41]:

# for logging differentiation dynamics
differentiation = []

for epoch in range (epochs):
    total_loss = 0
    #train loop
    for num, (image, label) in enumerate(tqdm(trainloader)):
        
        for i in range(3):
            
            #forward
            relation = torch.from_numpy(image_propositions[label*3+i][0][1])
            attribute = torch.from_numpy(image_propositions[label*3+i][1])
            logits, representation = model(image, relation)  
        
            #loss
            loss = lossfunction(logits, torch.unsqueeze(attribute, 0))
            total_loss += loss.item()
        
            #backward
            loss.backward()
        
            #update
            optimizer.step()
            optimizer.zero_grad()
            
        if epoch == 0:
            if (num == 0 or num == 10 or num == 50 or num == 200 
            or num == 10000 or num == len(trainloader)-1):
                # Here we track the differentiation progress of the network
                with torch.no_grad():
                    curr_progress = defaultdict(int)
                    # Iterate through test loader and calculate what the average entity representations are
                    for image, label in testloader:
                        curr_progress[label.item()] += model.image_to_rep(image).numpy()

                    # Rescale by the number of images for that entity
                    for label, representation in curr_progress.items():
                        curr_progress[label] = representation.flatten() / 1000

                    # Add current average representation to differentiation progress
                    differentiation.append(curr_progress)
        

    print(f"Loss: {total_loss/(len(trainloader))}")
    print()

From the clustering analysis it's clear to see that our intuition about how the representations would cluster is correct. We believed that the neural network algorithm would learn to cluster images that are taxonomically similar, this seems to be the case. The vehicles are clustered together and the animals are clustered together. Within vehicles car and truck are closer, and within animals cat and dog are close. The only aspect of the clustering that does not match our intuition is that deer is very similar to bird and frog as opposed to horse, dog, or cat. This not only does not match our intution about how the classes should cluster, but it is also unexpected based on the attributes that deer has. Deer has attributes that are most similar to horse, so we expected that it would cluster closely with horse. It's unclear as to why this is happening.


Additionally, it looks like the representations for each of the classes also reflect the idea of taxonomic similarity. This way of visualizing the representations is much more opaque than the clustering analysis so we will not discuss it here any further.























To push this point even further we wil now use a combination of PCA and K-means clustering to visually see the clusters. We utilize PCA so that we can reduce the dimensionality of the representations and actually visualize there relationships.


We will use a k-value of 5, which will stand for pairs of entities.


If our intuitions are correct we should be able to clearly see separations between the entities in each of the clusters. This would provide more support for the idea that our network is taxonomically clustering based on attribute.

Classification Performance¶






















So seeing those results a natural next question is whether or not this attribute based model actually performs better on classification tasks than a network trained only trained on classification. We may expect that since the attribute based network has learned these intermediate representations that it would be able to use that knowledge in order to make better classification predictions.


To test this we will uee transfer learning. We are going to utilize the convolutional part (image to representation part) of the neural network, attach it to a new set of fully connected layers, and train the network based on the original (unaugmented dataset). We will then compare the accuracy results of the attribute network with the results of a normal classification networks.


One reason to believe this will lead to a higher classification performance is evidence from what we know about semantic cognition in the human brain. The different attributes for each entity that were used to train the network (arugably) represent different modality-specific representations of knowledge we have about those entities. For example: having slimy_skin or fur and being big or fast are pieces of knowledge that can be gathered by different senses and can then be associated with the entity of focus. It is believed that we have an area in our brains (the anterior temporal lobe) that acts as a "semantic hub" that integrates modality dependent representations into a modality independent one (for more information see: https://royalsocietypublishing.org/doi/10.1098/rstb.2019.0301). So following this idea, it seems that we should be able to utilize the properties associated with each entity to increase classification performance to some degree.


So let's try it!


Here we create a simple linear network that utilizes the weights of the attribute network from above. We keep the architecture simple by just using linear and relu layers of modest size.



















In [47]:



     


class image_network_classification(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super(image_network_classification, self).__init__()
        
        
        self.classification_head = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(64, 64),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(64, 32),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(32, 10)
        )
        
        
    def forward(self, img):
        representation = model.image_to_rep(img)
        out = self.classification_head(representation)

        return out



     























We now instantiate the model. We only use 5 epochs so we can allow the model to learn while also avoiding overfitting. If we train too long we may overfit to the classification data.



















In [48]:



     


model_classifier = image_network_classification()

epochs = 5
learning_rate = 0.01

lossfunction = nn.CrossEntropyLoss()
optimizer_classification = optim.SGD(model_classifier.parameters(), lr=learning_rate)



     



















In [49]:



     


for epoch in range (epochs):
    total_loss = 0
    #train loop
    for image, label in tqdm(trainloader):

        logits = model_classifier(image)

        #loss
        loss = lossfunction(logits, label)
        total_loss += loss.item()

        #backward
        loss.backward()

        #update
        optimizer.step()
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        

    print(f"Loss: {total_loss/(len(trainloader))}")
    print()

Now that the net work has been trained for classification on the dataset, we will now test its performance by determining its accuracy on the testing data. At the same time to track the second guess the network made which will be analyzed below.



















In [50]:



     


# For logging second guesses
second_guess = defaultdict(lambda: defaultdict(int))
# Number of correct predictions
correct = 0

# No training => No grad required
with torch.no_grad():
    for image, label in testloader:
        
        # Get the top 2 predictions the model made based on its output
        logits = model_classifier(image)
        predicted_values, predicted_labels = torch.topk(logits.data, 2)
        
        # Map the prediction labels to the their entity names and log the frequency
        first_class = index_to_items[label.item()]
        second_class = index_to_items[predicted_labels[0][1].item()]
        second_guess[first_class][second_class] += 1
        
        correct += (predicted_labels == label).sum().item()
        
# Calculate the accuracy = number correct over total
print(f'Accuracy: {100 * (correct / len(testloader))}')



     






















    
    






Accuracy: 75.53




























Now that we have our models accuracy, we compare it to the accuracy of models that have been trained for classification on CIFAR-10 data. By looking at this: https://paperswithcode.com/sota/image-classification-on-cifar-10, it is clear that our attribute model does not perform as well as the top classification models. This could be attributed to many different factors including: model size, simplicity of architecture, etc. However, here we are more interested in how the network classifies. So to investigate this, we will look into the second best predictions the network made for the different images in the test set, and determine if it is making its second best guess based on taxonomic similarity.

From this it is clear to see that our network is working in ways that we would expect. For some of the classes, the second guesses are dominated by the class that was most similar to it (attribute wise) in the clustering analysis. For example: second guesses for dog were dominated by cat, the same is true for car and truck, ship and plane, the second guess of horse is deer, and the second guess for plane is bird. One interesting note is that deer is more evenly distributed than the other classes. However, despite this the seem to be obeying the taxonomy since most of their frequency falls with other living things as opposed to nonliving things.


Although this matches our intuition we will now perform a simple statistical test.


Here we use a chisquare frequency test to determine if the frequencies of the second guesses are significantly different from uniform.



















In [52]:



     


# Perform Chi-Square Frequency test for each entity second guesses
for label in second_guess:
    print(f"{label}: {chisquare(list(second_guess[label].values()))[1]}")

Conclusion¶






















Our analysis above leads us to believe that utilizing taxonomic similarity (and more generally handcrated features) can play a role in neural network learning algorithms. Although the network did not perform as well as the top CIFAR-10 classification models, it did perform withing the top 215 of percentage correct (at 77 percent). Additionally, by initially training with entity attributes it seems as though this model learns in ways that are more similar to human learning. It maps raw data to attributes and associates entities that have similar attributes. It is very interesting to see that the taxonomic organization that we observed with initially symbolic (entity-relation-attribute) analysis had similar results when using raw data.


Some extensions that could be done to further explore this area are: (1) utilizing datasets with larger class sets to determine if dataset size impacts the taxonomic organization - datasets like ImageNet (linked above) would be particularly useful (2) using a different set of entity attributes - since attributes are the learning signal, its clear that they control the representations, so how does changing them affect the entity representations (3) Seeing if a trained attribute model can generalize well to other classification datasets (4) Seeing if a trained attribute model is useful as a base for transfer learning on other computer vision tasks - a major one being video action classification. In video action classification (or temporal action localization) the signal is much more sparse than in image classification. The tensor representation of videos are much larger and yet they still have to be mapped to single classes. Using an attribute trained model as a backbone could help boost performance.
